38    /**
39    * Implements the Gregorian/Julian calendar system which is the calendar system
40    * used in most of the world. Wherever possible, it is recommended to use the
41    * {@link ISOChronology} instead.
42    * <p>
43    * The Gregorian calendar replaced the Julian calendar, and the point in time
44    * when this chronology switches can be controlled using the second parameter
45    * of the getInstance method. By default this cutover is set to the date the
46    * Gregorian calendar was first instituted, October 15, 1582.
47    * <p>
48    * Before this date, this chronology uses the proleptic Julian calendar
49    * (proleptic means extending indefinitely). The Julian calendar has leap years
50    * every four years, whereas the Gregorian has special rules for 100 and 400
51    * years. A meaningful result will thus be obtained for all input values.
52    * However before 8 CE, Julian leap years were irregular, and before 45 BCE
53    * there was no Julian calendar.
54    * <p>
55    * This chronology differs from
56    * {@link java.util.GregorianCalendar GregorianCalendar} in that years
57    * in BCE are returned correctly. Thus year 1 BCE is returned as -1 instead of 1.
58    * The yearOfEra field produces results compatible with GregorianCalendar.
59    * <p>
60    * The Julian calendar does not have a year zero, and so year -1 is followed by
61    * year 1. If the Gregorian cutover date is specified at or before year -1
62    * (Julian), year zero is defined. In other words, the proleptic Gregorian
63    * chronology used by this class has a year zero.
64    * <p>
65    * To create a pure proleptic Julian chronology, use {@link JulianChronology},
66    * and to create a pure proleptic Gregorian chronology, use
67    * {@link GregorianChronology}.
68    * <p>
69    * GJChronology is thread-safe and immutable.
70    *
71    * @author Brian S O'Neill
72    * @author Stephen Colebourne
73    * @since 1.0
74    */

1117    // reduce the number of months in a year. If the missing month(s) are
1118    // at the beginning or end of the year, then the minimum and maximum
1119    // values are not 1 and 12. I don't expect this case to ever occur.
